FINAL FOR RESTRUCTURE:

   1. Executive summary

  You should implement this as a clean-slate cutover, not a compatibility migration. The target state is one
  canonical action execution path for all business operations, and every channel (API routes, assistant tools,
  internal jobs) must use that path directly. No dual-mode routing, no legacy fallbacks, no compatibility aliases.

  The architecture should introduce a new dedicated runtime package, @jskit-ai/action-runtime-core, and keep @jskit-
  ai/server-runtime-core focused on generic server primitives. Domain packages/modules will own their action
  contributors (definitions + handlers), and the app composition root will explicitly mount contributors into a
  central registry. This aligns with your existing composition pattern in server/runtime/services.js (/home/merc/
  Development/current/jskit-ai/apps/jskit-value-app/server/runtime/services.js) and server/runtime/
  platformModuleManifest.js (/home/merc/Development/current/jskit-ai/apps/jskit-value-app/server/runtime/
  platformModuleManifest.js).

  Current behavior is fragmented across controllers/services/tools (for example workspaceRename.tool.js (/home/merc/
  Development/current/jskit-ai/apps/jskit-value-app/server/modules/ai/lib/tools/workspaceRename.tool.js), direct
  controller audit wrappers in package adapters, and route-level policy metadata). The new plan centralizes
  permission checks, audit emission, idempotency, validation, and observability in the action pipeline itself. Route
  policy remains as defense-in-depth, but action policy is authoritative.

  This plan uses actions_map.md (/home/merc/Development/current/jskit-ai/actions_map.md) as canonical action
  inventory and naming baseline, and assumes your explicit constraints: no backward compatibility paths and a new
  action-runtime-core package.

  2. Proposed architecture model

  Action definition contract

  - id: canonical ID from actions_map.md (/home/merc/Development/current/jskit-ai/actions_map.md), example
    workspace.invite.create.
  - version: integer, start at 1 for all initial actions.
  - domain: auth | settings | workspace | projects | chat | billing | console | assistant | deg2rad_history.
  - kind: query | command | stream.
  - channels: explicit channel allowlist, example ["api","assistant_tool","internal"].
  - surfaces: explicit surface allowlist, example ["app","admin"] or ["console"].
  - visibility: public | internal | operator.
  - inputSchema: canonical schema used by action runtime (code-defined; not DB/JSON file driven).
  - outputSchema: optional response contract schema for action-level validation/consistency.
  - permission: static permission list or dynamic resolver (context, input) => boolean/deny.
  - idempotency: none | optional | required | domain_native.
  - audit: { actionName, metadataBuilder, piiTags }.
  - observability: metric tags and sampling hints.
  - execute: handler (input, context, deps) => result.

  Action contributor contract

  - Contributor factory is explicit and pure: createXActionContributor(deps).
  - Returns { contributorId, domain, actions }.
  - No side-effect registration at import time.
  - Contributor boot validation fails on malformed definitions.
  - Duplicate action IDs across contributors are hard startup errors.

  Registry contract

  - createActionRegistry({ contributors, permissionEvaluator, idempotencyAdapter, auditAdapter,
    observabilityAdapter, logger }).
  - execute({ actionId, version, input, context }).
  - executeStream(...) for streaming actions like assistant.chat.stream.
  - listDefinitions() and getDefinition(actionId, version?).
  - Pipeline order:
  - resolve action definition
  - enforce channel and surface gates
  - validate input
  - enforce permission policy
  - resolve idempotency claim/replay
  - execute handler
  - emit audit and metrics
  - return normalized result
  - No route/controller bypass API is exposed.

  Execution context contract

  - actor: normalized identity from request/user/session.
  - workspace: normalized workspace context, nullable.
  - membership: membership summary when workspace-scoped.
  - permissions: resolved permission set for actor+surface+workspace.
  - surface: app | admin | console.
  - channel: api | assistant_tool | assistant_chat | internal | worker.
  - requestMeta: requestId, commandId, idempotencyKey, ip, user-agent.
  - assistantMeta: conversationId, toolCallId, provider, turnId when relevant.
  - timeMeta: now, timezone/locale hints if needed.
  - Build this via one shared adapter so API and assistant contexts are structurally identical.

